{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:57:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1009"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1009"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.76,0.04,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1009"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1009"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18533"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"253"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year old man is being reviewed 42 hours after an exploratory laparotomy for a perforated peptic ulcer. Over the last 24 hours he has become short of breath. On examination his blood pressure is 115/70 mmHg, pulse 104/min, temperature 37.4C and respiratory rate 24/min. Chest auscultation shows reduced breath sounds over the lower lobe bilaterally. His calves are soft and not tender. A chest X-ray shows bilateral homogenous opacification of the lower lobes of the lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumonia","Atelectasis","Pulmonary embolism","Pneumothorax","Pneumonitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common postoperative complication, typically occurring within 72 hours of surgery. This diagnosis is likely in this case as the patient has developed acute dyspnoea, tachycardia, and tachypnoea. The X-ray findings correspond to an area of partial lung collapse. The clinical presentation of this patient is consistent with atelectasis, including reduced breath sounds over the lower lobe bilaterally and homogenous opacification of the lower lobes bilaterally on chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the lungs, which typically presents with symptoms such as cough, fever, chest pain, and shortness of breath. it is most commonly seen after 48 hours and within the first five days after surgery. The risk of pneumonia increases with certain factors such as advanced age, pre-existing lung disease, smoking, prolonged anaesthesia time, prolonged mechanical ventilation and impaired immune function. Some common signs and symptoms of postoperative pneumonia include fever, cough with or without sputum production, chest pain, shortness of breath, and abnormal chest auscultation. On examination, there may be crackles or rales heard over the affected area of the lung, and chest X-ray may show focal infiltrates. Whilst a possible diagnosis in this patient, pneumonia is less likely that pulmonary atelectasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E pulmonary embolism (PE)\u003C/strong\u003E is a less likely cause of this patient\u0027s problems, as unless there are pre-existing factors, such an event would not be expected to occur so soon after surgery. However, the risk of postoperative pulmonary embolism remains significantly elevated between 7 and 12 weeks after surgery. While PE can occur after surgery, it is less common than atelectasis or pneumonia and it is not associated with bilateral lower lobe opacification on chest X-ray. The main symptoms are sudden shortness of breath (most common), chest pain (usually worse with breathing), a feeling of anxiety, a feeling of dizziness, lightheadedness, or fainting, irregular heartbeat and palpitations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E pneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E would be an uncommon occurrence after abdominal surgery. The main symptoms to be expected would be a sharp, stabbing chest pain that worsens when trying to breath in. There is likely to be short of breath and whilst this patient\u0027s dyspnoea could be explained by a pneumothorax, the chest X-ray does not show any evidence of lung collapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammation of the lung tissue, which can be caused by a variety of factors including infection, exposure to toxic substances or autoimmune disease. In postoperative patients, pneumonitis can occur within the first few days to weeks after surgery, particularly in those who have undergone thoracic or upper abdominal procedures. The symptoms would be fever, chills, muscle or joint pain and headache. On examination, there may be crackles or rales heard over the affected area of the lung, and the chest X-ray may show focal infiltrates. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-operative basal atelectasis is a common event and usually of no clinical significance."],"references":["Grott K, Chauhan S, Dunlap JD. Atelectasis. [Updated 2022 Oct 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18533"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1009"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18533"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-27T14:52:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-02-27T14:52:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1009"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data